00:28:13,159 --> 00:28:13,460
Freedom.

477
00:28:13,520 --> 00:28:14,540
Yeah, freedom.

478
00:28:14,560 --> 00:28:16,242
Hard times as well, but freedom.

479
00:28:16,502 --> 00:28:17,323
Yeah, yeah.

480
00:28:17,363 --> 00:28:18,003
Freedom, definitely.

481
00:28:18,043 --> 00:28:19,805
Yeah, see, this is why you bring your crew with you.

482
00:28:20,005 --> 00:28:22,106
You ain't got it, they got it for you.

483
00:28:22,166 --> 00:28:23,628
All right, very good, very good.

484
00:28:23,868 --> 00:28:25,269
OK, allies.

485
00:28:26,230 --> 00:28:26,650
Important.

486
00:28:26,990 --> 00:28:28,511
Very important, very important.

487
00:28:28,932 --> 00:28:32,234
And then last one is your edge.

488
00:28:32,895 --> 00:28:34,116
What is your edge?

489
00:28:36,805 --> 00:28:54,332
My edge is tolerating or non-tolerance of racism from anyone.

490
00:28:54,672 --> 00:28:59,054
That right there sends me over the edge.

491
00:28:59,234 --> 00:29:00,275
I still know the ledge.

492
00:29:01,295 --> 00:29:03,877
I still know the list, so I know how to walk on those conditions.

493
00:29:03,937 --> 00:29:05,719
I get it, I get it, I get it, I get it.

494
00:29:05,839 --> 00:29:12,264
Okay, so I'm going to, I want to take it in a slightly different direction because you took it in one direction.

495
00:29:13,245 --> 00:29:17,208
When I say your edge, I mean, you know, your advantage over the other guy.

496
00:29:17,268 --> 00:29:18,349
Okay, gotcha, gotcha.

497
00:29:18,749 --> 00:29:20,010
Okay, so what is my edge?

498
00:29:20,050 --> 00:29:21,812
Yeah.

499
00:29:22,573 --> 00:29:25,035
My edge, it's several things.

500
00:29:25,055 --> 00:29:25,135
Okay.

501
00:29:30,808 --> 00:29:46,579
reasons why I do what I do, why I don't do a lot of the things that were in front of me to do and in front of me is because I would never want to upset my family or let my family down or disgrace my family name because my family didn't raise me like that.

502
00:29:47,860 --> 00:29:49,421
Another one is thinking for self.

503
00:29:51,062 --> 00:29:57,186
Thinking for self, over time it proved that, you know, that was the right thing to do because there's a lot of influences.

504
00:29:57,546 --> 00:30:00,028
A lot of people are lost, are wandering around.

505
00:30:02,247 --> 00:30:03,808
Okay, that's perfect, that's perfect.

506
00:30:04,109 --> 00:30:08,712
So I'm going to give you the last word, okay, as I usually try and do.

507
00:30:08,832 --> 00:30:11,293
So what do you want the people out there to know about you?

508
00:30:12,714 --> 00:30:19,459
Well, I mean, you pretty much heard quite a bit, and there is so much more, but I'm not going to get into all that.

509
00:30:19,799 --> 00:30:25,803
What I do want you to know about me is the elephant in the room is going to be here.

510
00:30:26,403 --> 00:30:29,746
So look for more items, more products, more pop-ups.

511
00:30:30,464 --> 00:30:35,507
more conversations, and more doors to open.

512
00:30:35,527 --> 00:30:38,189
I mean, there's going to be another chapter to the book.

513
00:30:38,229 --> 00:30:43,633
I don't know what it's going to be yet, but this just opened me up to a whole other realm.

514
00:30:43,873 --> 00:30:53,319
And again, there's a lot in me that I would like to get out, have to get it out the right way, articulate, and make an impact.

515
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:56,261
But yeah, so we have some merch over here.

516
00:30:56,281 --> 00:30:58,843
If anyone is interested, at the end of the day,

517
00:31:01,330 --> 00:31:28,360
lectures and the book of course and just look out for the elephant in the room and check out the website okay all right all right all right so yeah the website is elephantintheroom.etsy.com okay elephantintheroom.etsy.com and I have business cards here as well okay fantastic fantastic so thank you

518
00:31:29,713 --> 00:31:36,536
bringing your business and your philosophical insights to our cultural community in greater Medford.

519
00:31:37,217 --> 00:31:42,739
It's a unique venture that you created and a challenging vision in the current social landscape.

520
00:31:43,400 --> 00:31:48,442
And to our audience, both here and elsewhere, thanks so much for your attentiveness.

521
00:31:50,745 --> 00:31:59,611
Thanks for coming along with us as we continue to refresh for greater flexibility and bring you the best stories and entertainment we can.

522
00:32:00,472 --> 00:32:04,955
Get ready for something hopefully special on the musical side of the coin.

523
00:32:05,295 --> 00:32:12,540
We're going to take a break to reset our stage and be back and share some WMCC announcements

524
00:32:20,135 --> 00:32:25,598
Bravo, bravissimo, primo extraordinaire.

525
00:32:25,798 --> 00:32:35,584
All right, okay, all right, let's shift the room.

526
00:32:41,047 --> 00:32:43,228
I think we need a new cutting.

527
00:32:43,508 --> 00:32:46,170
Could I, would you like two of us?

528
00:37:34,872 --> 00:37:45,238
close-ups, the camera might fight him, but do your best.

529
00:37:45,578 --> 00:37:50,281
All right, everybody can grab a seat.

530
00:37:50,381 --> 00:37:58,106
And we promise there'll be time for, you know, your purchases and your snooping around and your conversations after, right?

531
00:37:58,246 --> 00:38:00,587
We won't kick you out.

532
00:38:01,027 --> 00:38:03,629
Spend as much time with us as you like.

533
00:38:05,060 --> 00:38:05,981
All right, so.

534
00:38:06,001 --> 00:38:08,303
All right, so.

535
00:38:08,363 --> 00:38:14,108
It's poetry month, and I'm greedy.

536
00:38:33,493 --> 00:38:41,762
I like to have as many opportunities as possible to get out there with my poet-type friends, one of which is in the room.

537
00:38:41,802 --> 00:38:43,263
I can see Robert back there.

538
00:38:44,585 --> 00:38:51,872
And we like to go around to as many invitations as we get and do poetry.

539
00:39:00,828 --> 00:39:05,230
So I get to, I get to.

540
00:39:05,350 --> 00:39:09,132
And so every once in a while, I get to do what I want to do.

541
00:39:09,172 --> 00:39:10,552
Not very often, OK?

542
00:39:10,572 --> 00:39:15,695
Because I got bosses that, you know, several of whom are in the room, so.

543
00:39:17,375 --> 00:39:26,600
But joining me in a celebration of Poetry Month are dear friends, collaborators,

544
00:39:28,922 --> 00:39:31,044
And we call ourselves the Ally Project.

545
00:39:31,264 --> 00:39:36,749
And the Ally Project is really, really the brainchild of Jonathan Fagan.

546
00:39:41,593 --> 00:39:45,937
And Jonathan and I have known each other for several years now.

547
00:39:45,957 --> 00:39:54,344
And we first got together behind Jonathan hearing me do something somewhere and saying, you know what?

548
00:39:55,017 --> 00:40:02,560
it would be interesting to see if, you know, what I love and what he loves could somehow, you know, come together.

549
00:40:02,620 --> 00:40:07,322
So, and we always say we met at the intersection of jazz and social justice.

550
00:40:08,062 --> 00:40:10,763
So, you know, I was, yeah.

551
00:40:12,444 --> 00:40:16,725
I was social justice street and he was jazz avenue.

552
00:40:16,905 --> 00:40:18,726
And now it's kind of,

553
00:40:19,105 --> 00:40:25,046
You can't really tell where the jazz stops and where the social justice starts and vice versa.

554
00:40:25,066 --> 00:40:26,887
So it's real cool.

555
00:40:26,907 --> 00:40:32,208
But Jonathan is also the impresario behind the Medford Jazz Festival.

556
00:40:32,928 --> 00:40:38,969
So if you haven't been, we've had it here for the last several years.

557
00:40:40,290 --> 00:40:45,991
And we'll be having it again on the third weekend, second or third weekend in August.

558
00:40:46,575 --> 00:40:48,036
right out in the backyard here.

559
00:40:48,136 --> 00:40:51,420
And it's going to be a big event for the community center.

560
00:40:51,440 --> 00:40:52,521
We love hosting it.

561
00:40:54,442 --> 00:41:02,189
But we've had the opportunity to do some really, really cool stuff together in literally dozens of places.

562
00:41:03,030 --> 00:41:09,316
The original Memphis Jazz Festival, which actually ended up being a studio exercise because it was during the COVID.

563
00:41:10,638 --> 00:41:17,586
So we did it as a studio, in a studio, and it was broadcast in YouTube and all of that stuff.

564
00:41:17,966 --> 00:41:24,374
And we've also cut a studio CD and done some recent work with classical string music ensembles, right?

565
00:41:24,694 --> 00:41:27,958
Which is a whole nother flavor, you know, when you add that.

566
00:41:28,394 --> 00:41:33,997
to the jazz, and we're hoping that at some point in time we can maybe do that here as well.

567
00:41:34,057 --> 00:41:40,041
But anyways, Jonathan, he's an incredible pianist, he's an arranger, he's a composer, and he's a band leader.

568
00:41:40,081 --> 00:41:44,463
He teaches music in Concord and probably half a dozen other places.

569
00:41:44,964 --> 00:41:47,405
And he has two big, floppy-eared bunnies.

570
00:41:48,466 --> 00:41:49,827
Does he look like a bunny guy?

571
00:41:50,847 --> 00:41:53,889
He's a funny guy, but does he look like a bunny guy?

572
00:41:53,909 --> 00:41:55,590
But anyways, the bunnies are wonderful.

573
00:41:57,959 --> 00:42:02,603
He has them with his partner in crime, Sheila.

574
00:42:02,763 --> 00:42:05,886
And they're an interesting, they're too interesting.

575
00:42:05,906 --> 00:42:09,249
Yeah, they're very interesting.

576
00:42:09,309 --> 00:42:10,189
In a good way.

577
00:42:10,229 --> 00:42:13,452
Yeah, in a very good way, but sometimes not so good, but you know.

578
00:42:15,214 --> 00:42:18,116
Well, because they, you know, they can't get it together sometimes.

579
00:42:18,156 --> 00:42:23,000
They just be in love with each other the way, because bunnies, you know, bunnies.

580
00:42:26,636 --> 00:42:29,418
I'm sorry, that's my stand-up.

581
00:42:29,478 --> 00:42:35,883
So Julian, John, and me, Greg Toro and the big sexy over here, all right?

582
00:42:37,865 --> 00:42:41,928
And my man, he really can pat him, just go to that angle guy on the drums.

583
00:42:42,328 --> 00:42:44,530
And again, together we are the Ally Project.

584
00:42:46,922 --> 00:42:55,567
And so we're going to continue the conversation that I was having with my man, Smitty, at the intersection of jazz and social justice.

585
00:42:55,968 --> 00:42:57,168
So strap yourselves in.

586
00:42:57,228 --> 00:42:58,349
It's going to be a bumpy ride.

587
00:42:59,450 --> 00:42:59,950
All right?

588
00:43:00,210 --> 00:43:00,790
All right.

589
00:43:01,391 --> 00:43:01,771
How about it?

590
00:43:09,199 --> 00:43:16,025
They gave my people the lowlands, and not much of it, just a few streets high by the river.

591
00:43:16,185 --> 00:43:18,567
Banks turned a blind eye behind the red lines.

592
00:43:18,627 --> 00:43:21,009
And it wasn't about the money.

593
00:43:21,069 --> 00:43:23,871
Class was an irresistible force.

594
00:43:29,009 --> 00:43:44,826
Perhaps it wasn't a written rule, but white folks knew the legal tool to keep us in our place in this mystic valley space where slaves and rum and chips had built some mansions, made some millionaires, and hid some old money.

595
00:43:47,589 --> 00:43:51,853
So it was hot by the mystic we went, money and a big turn down.

596
00:43:53,212 --> 00:43:57,395
where one could be found in this ancient Middlesex County town.

597
00:43:57,715 --> 00:44:05,421
But we named it, we claimed it, we made it our own.

598
00:44:05,782 --> 00:44:18,771
Even in the heat of summer when the shores were parched and the soil was rank with the decay of aquatic alchemy, we were one with the river.

599
00:44:18,811 --> 00:44:20,993
We followed its flow to the lakes

600
00:44:29,989 --> 00:44:35,713
On our own Jordan shore, we baptized and blessed our brothers and sisters in Christ.

601
00:44:35,753 --> 00:44:47,502
We caught the little fishes to go with our loaves of bread and became the team of multitude whom our Lord Jesus fed, hired by the mystic.

602
00:44:47,562 --> 00:44:48,923
We became community.

603
00:44:48,943 --> 00:44:50,544
We commanded unity.

604
00:44:50,604 --> 00:44:54,847
We embraced the village and raised up our children in the way they should go.

605
00:45:00,661 --> 00:45:04,704
As the river ebbs and flows, the tide can turn and our fortune grows.

606
00:45:05,224 --> 00:45:07,045
A few more streets become our home.

607
00:45:07,465 --> 00:45:10,647
Houses on Sharon join, kin on Jerome.

608
00:45:11,147 --> 00:45:19,632
From Duggar Park to the railroad tracks, the color line recedes a bit, and the white folks make more room for blacks.

609
00:45:19,992 --> 00:45:21,873
Church and school has such a fit.

610
00:45:21,913 --> 00:45:26,296
DeVille becomes a part of it, hard by the misty shores.

611
00:45:42,233 --> 00:45:47,535
Now the world has surely turned, and folks who left have surely turned.

612
00:45:47,595 --> 00:45:50,617
Things couldn't stay the same.

613
00:45:50,817 --> 00:45:53,558
The money mystic most days is clean.

614
00:45:53,618 --> 00:45:56,199
The banks are freshly cut and green.

615
00:45:56,980 --> 00:46:01,041
Faces once distinctly brown are not the only ones in town.

616
00:46:15,158 --> 00:46:30,282
All confines must now embrace what gentry defines, condominium culture, bedroom convicts, university sprawl, access, egress, invest, and dispossess.

617
00:46:30,342 --> 00:46:43,746
Now those lowlands have become the highlights of a trending city, and sometimes that success isn't pretty when it's at the expense of your black and brown and tan friends.

618
00:46:52,602 --> 00:46:59,569
And yet, the river still turns and bends from where it begins to where it ends.

619
00:47:00,510 --> 00:47:13,983
The only place where one can be found in this ancient Middlesex County town, where we named it, and claimed it, and made it our own.

620
00:47:22,625 --> 00:47:28,594
All right, so continuing in a similar vein, we're going to do a piece called Cornelot.

621
00:47:28,614 --> 00:47:31,138
It's another West Medford poem.

622
00:48:14,552 --> 00:48:20,735
standing at the apex of Arlington and Jerome, trying to remember the black and the brown and the tan.

623
00:48:21,796 --> 00:48:24,957
Ronnie and Otis used to live in the big house on the corner lot.

624
00:48:25,838 --> 00:48:28,940
It's probably changed hands half a dozen times since then.

625
00:48:30,040 --> 00:48:31,981
Conrad only's been there for a minute.

626
00:48:32,521 --> 00:48:36,824
He's good with his hands and knows his way around wood and tools.

627
00:48:37,464 --> 00:48:39,265
Place has been dusted up quite a bit.

628
00:48:40,166 --> 00:48:42,847
Picket fence is off-white, but if you know,

629
00:48:50,114 --> 00:48:53,778
Asian kid in a Tufts hoodie just whipped by in a helmet with rollerblades.

630
00:48:53,798 --> 00:48:56,521
Didn't see much of that back in the day.

631
00:48:56,541 --> 00:49:02,406
The university sort of hit on the hillside, trying its best to be a baby Ivy.

632
00:49:02,466 --> 00:49:05,510
But the co-eds come here all the time now.

633
00:49:06,070 --> 00:49:13,418
Basketballs, tennis rackets, and football paddles in tow on bikes, benzos, and rollerblades.

634
00:49:15,427 --> 00:49:21,468
We used to bust ourselves up pretty good on rickety metal skates, clunky keys, and leather straps.

635
00:49:22,129 --> 00:49:25,229
Nothing a little Vaseline and Mercurochrome couldn't handle.

636
00:49:25,890 --> 00:49:27,630
How did Henley put it in Invictus?

637
00:49:28,290 --> 00:49:30,311
Oh, yeah, bloody but unbowed.

638
00:49:31,511 --> 00:49:35,432
Not too many white and off-white kids hanging out down here back then.

639
00:49:36,392 --> 00:49:43,154
It was as if the invisible lines once drawn to keep us in sometimes kept the other folks out, too.

640
00:49:50,065 --> 00:49:51,546
they've pretty much taken over.

641
00:49:52,047 --> 00:49:56,251
Duggar Park, the Rhone Tennis Court, and Hervey's School Yard.

642
00:49:57,012 --> 00:50:01,496
And a hundred addresses on Arlington, Lincoln, and Jerome.

643
00:50:01,636 --> 00:50:07,562
A host of our remembered places, so few of our original faces.

644
00:50:31,913 --> 00:50:36,496
Meanwhile, back at Ronnie and Otis' old place, I'm still standing.

645
00:50:37,456 --> 00:50:41,979
Like that centurion, knowing that Jesus doesn't have to go in to heal the servant.

646
00:50:42,059 --> 00:50:43,600
He just has to speak a word.

647
00:50:44,921 --> 00:50:52,265
I guess I keep hoping that he'll speak a word to the corner lot, too, and bring back the black and the brown and the tan.

648
00:50:54,800 --> 00:50:56,222
Across the street is the river.

649
00:50:57,022 --> 00:51:04,110
It's low tide, but the smell is gone, and the grass is greener than I recall.

650
00:51:06,312 --> 00:51:10,777
That was our little park, away from Dublin, a lot less hectic.

651
00:51:11,438 --> 00:51:16,022
We had makeshift bases or discarded cones for football and softball.

652
00:51:17,109 --> 00:51:22,394
We lost a few balls in the river, but nobody was going into that muck to retrieve anything.

653
00:51:23,315 --> 00:51:25,196
We'd probably wade in that water today.

654
00:51:26,916 --> 00:51:29,317
They planted some trees there many years ago.

655
00:51:29,877 --> 00:51:31,457
They're all pretty big now.

656
00:51:32,257 --> 00:51:34,018
Maple and ash, I think.

657
00:51:35,018 --> 00:51:47,081
Nobody plays baseball or football there anymore, but there are a lot of dogs frolicking off-leash and gaggles of fat geese daring pitties, pugs, and poodles to chase them off.

658
00:51:49,910 --> 00:51:53,892
I can't imagine my childhood without losing a few softballs there.

659
00:51:54,913 --> 00:52:06,438
I can't imagine not hearing Mrs. Allen calling James Michael to come eat, or a little Charlie watching us play from his folding chair because his spinning legs were too weak to let him run.

660
00:52:07,319 --> 00:52:18,084
I can't imagine that I'm still here, but Ronnie and Otis, Darryl King, Frankie French, Aaron McDaniel, Michael Davis are all

661
00:52:25,352 --> 00:52:28,235
Everyone had a nickname back then.

662
00:52:28,255 --> 00:52:31,838
Daryl was super fast, so we called him Roadrunner Jackrabbit.

663
00:52:32,939 --> 00:52:37,524
Mark was as thick as a big oak tree, so we came up with oak for him.

664
00:52:38,404 --> 00:52:42,929
Eric was fun, Frankie was fruit man, and I was top cat.

665
00:52:43,429 --> 00:52:44,991
Too cool, ran to school.

666
00:52:47,993 --> 00:52:56,359
Everyone wants the corner lot, a little more land, and perhaps the new angles that, the new perspectives that angles create.

667
00:52:58,660 --> 00:53:06,825
I wonder if that meant anything to Ronnie and Otis, or Jed, or Miles, or Gil, or Barry, or Coco, or Keith, or Kenny, or Byfield.

668
00:53:07,806 --> 00:53:15,431
It certainly meant something to the white folk looking to displace, transplant, and uproot below the color.

669
00:53:21,107 --> 00:53:33,556
Black folks built homes here, only place where they were allowed to be, where they could color inside the lines Medford once drew against the perceived discomforts of darker skin.

670
00:53:34,777 --> 00:53:46,005
We were here first, first firefighters, police officers, war heroes, shop owners, tradesmen, postal chiefs, teachers, artists, and preachers.

671
00:53:47,988 --> 00:53:52,251
We were the human bedrock of the only neighborhood they let us build.

672
00:53:54,373 --> 00:53:55,673
The old church is gone.

673
00:53:56,494 --> 00:54:07,762
Nelson even changed the street number from 33 to 35 Lincoln, as if to erase the fact that the original Shiloh Baptist ever existed.

674
00:54:08,062 --> 00:54:10,104
But if you know, you know.

675
00:54:11,303 --> 00:54:15,965
That corner lot still has a corner stone.

676
00:54:15,985 --> 00:54:21,587
1900, and Nelson couldn't do nothing about it without a more draconian demolition.

677
00:54:27,930 --> 00:54:30,491
Two more condos in the house of the Lord.

678
00:54:31,191 --> 00:54:34,593
Two more houses that our sparse folk can't afford.

679
00:54:35,753 --> 00:54:39,015
Two more dismissals of the blessings of his word.

680
00:54:40,174 --> 00:54:46,158
One more holy stone rejected and ignored.

681
00:54:46,639 --> 00:54:47,519
Thank you.

682
00:54:47,599 --> 00:54:48,180
Thank you.

683
00:54:48,240 --> 00:54:48,760
Thank you.

684
00:54:48,840 --> 00:54:50,502
Thank you so much.

685
00:54:50,542 --> 00:54:51,983
The name of Cornelot.

686
00:54:52,043 --> 00:54:52,303
Yeah.

687
00:54:52,343 --> 00:54:52,823
Let me see.

688
00:54:52,863 --> 00:54:53,344
Let me see.

689
00:55:22,067 --> 00:55:22,768
Moving parts.

690
00:55:23,568 --> 00:55:24,969
We've got a lot of moving parts.

691
00:55:26,550 --> 00:55:32,635
Your music and poetry is so beautiful.

692
00:55:33,975 --> 00:55:36,517
Thank you.

693
00:55:44,403 --> 00:55:47,165
Thank you very much.

694
00:55:47,185 --> 00:55:47,745
All right.

695
00:55:48,186 --> 00:55:49,246
